statement.p:
Considering the set of vectors \vvec=\twovec{-2}{1} and \wvec = \twovec{8}{-4}, we see that the vector
\bvec = 3\vvec + \wvec = \twovec2{-1}
is one vector in the span of the vectors \vvec and \wvec because it is a linear combination of \vvec and \wvec.

li.p:
We have the reduced row echelon form
\left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp -2 \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Since there is a pivot position in every row, this says that every equation A\xvec=\bvec is consistent. The \laspan{\vvec_1, \vvec_2, \vvec_3} is therefore \real^3.

statement.p:
Let \vvec be a nonzero vector in
\real^3. Explain why 
\laspan{\vvec}
is always an infinite set of vectors and describe
\laspan{\vvec}
geometrically.

match.premise:
If \vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{n} are vectors
in \real^{23} and
A= \begin{bmatrix}
\vvec_1\amp\vvec_2\amp\cdots\amp\vvec_{n}
\end{bmatrix}
has a pivot in every row, then 
\laspan{\vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{n}}=\real^{23}.

If \vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{23} are vectors
in \real^{23} and
\laspan{\vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{23}}=\real^{23}, then  
A= \begin{bmatrix}
\vvec_1\amp\vvec_2\amp\cdots\amp\vvec_{23}
\end{bmatrix} 
has a pivot in every column.

If \vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{n} are vectors
in \real^{23} and
A= \begin{bmatrix}
\vvec_1\amp\vvec_2\amp\cdots\amp\vvec_{n}
\end{bmatrix}
has a pivot in every column, then 
\laspan{\vvec_1,\ldots,\vvec_{n}}=\real^{23}.
